{"id":14881761,"mediaExerciseId":"1970e93f-d5d8-48ef-83f5-aa53a6a6889b","exerciseName":"3","chapterName":"21","chapterTitle":"International Corporate Finance","groupId":612470,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":735,"solutions":[{"id":5977857,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we will apply what we have learned about exchange rates.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/9cc1e9c028f9a1804d3be7cafc1daac2/1e5c2018fe270dc5d76946575ccf08ba/lateximg_large.png","width":986},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/9cc1e9c028f9a1804d3be7cafc1daac2/1e5c2018fe270dc5d76946575ccf08ba/lateximg.png","width":493}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The exercise states that the exchange rate of Australian dollar is currently A$1.40 and is expected to rise by 10% next year.\n\\\nAn **Exchange Rate** is the value of a country's currency when *expressed in another country's currency*.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"## a.\n\nWe are asked to determine if the Australian dollar is expected to get stronger or weaker.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"If there is an increase in the exchange rate, this means *more Australian dollars* are required to exchange for U.S. dollars. Therefore, the Australian dollar is expected to get **weaker** since it is expected to rise by 10% next year. The higher the exchange rate, the more Australian dollars required to purchase U.S. dollar.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"## b.\n\nWe are asked to give insights about the relative inflation rates in the United States and Australia.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"A **relative purchasing power parity** refers to the concept that there is a *change in exchange rate* that can be determined by the *difference of the inflation rate* of two countries. Moreover, there is an *inverse relationship* between the value of the currency and the inflation rate. The higher the value of the currency, the lower the inflation rate.  ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/9cc1e9c028f9a1804d3be7cafc1daac2/8c7d86cfa47a82d30b8b733c05d1d5b6/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/9cc1e9c028f9a1804d3be7cafc1daac2/8c7d86cfa47a82d30b8b733c05d1d5b6/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"Since the exchange rate of the Australian dollar is expected to increase by 10% the following year, the Australian dollar is expected to get weaker making the inflation rate of the Australia **higher** compared to the inflation rate of United States. A higher inflation rate decreases the purchasing power of Australia since more Australian dollars are required to purchase a U.S. dollar.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7},{"columns":[{"text":"## c.\n\nWe are asked to give insights about the relative nominal interest rates and real interest rates in the United States and Australia.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":8},{"columns":[{"text":"The nominal interest rate of Australia will relatively be **higher** than the nominal interest rate of the United States because of the  increasing inflation rate of Australia.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":100,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/9cc1e9c028f9a1804d3be7cafc1daac2/fa47aa329e5fe655aad28d8281a7a732/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":51,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/9cc1e9c028f9a1804d3be7cafc1daac2/fa47aa329e5fe655aad28d8281a7a732/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":9},{"columns":[{"text":"On the other hand, the real interest rates of United States and Australia are the **same** because of the International Fisher Effect. The international fisher effect states that the real rates are equal across countries to prevent the money from flowing out from the financial markets.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/9cc1e9c028f9a1804d3be7cafc1daac2/81c69f36f11a8c9255b44c45d4995986/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/9cc1e9c028f9a1804d3be7cafc1daac2/81c69f36f11a8c9255b44c45d4995986/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":10},{"columns":[{"text":"As a conclusion, we have applied what we have learned about exchange rates.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":61,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/9cc1e9c028f9a1804d3be7cafc1daac2/93d4b79c3236e32f526a0a84e430353d/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":32,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/9cc1e9c028f9a1804d3be7cafc1daac2/93d4b79c3236e32f526a0a84e430353d/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":11}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"fb761d7c-7411-4091-85c0-b0d367c619fe","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":11}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881762,"exerciseName":"4","page":735,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"f8ea0464-7797-427c-a01b-074c16ba668c","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-21-critical-thinking-questions-4-f8ea0464-7797-427c-a01b-074c16ba668c"},{"id":14881763,"exerciseName":"5","page":735,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"2ef1fe97-04c9-47d6-884d-fffb45af5645","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-21-critical-thinking-questions-5-2ef1fe97-04c9-47d6-884d-fffb45af5645"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881760,"exerciseName":"2","page":735,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"fa4d8b42-30d1-45d6-aa1f-6c1ee163d0be","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-21-critical-thinking-questions-2-fa4d8b42-30d1-45d6-aa1f-6c1ee163d0be"},{"id":14881759,"exerciseName":"1","page":735,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"7e8e1f42-f8d1-4547-b25e-cd82260b69c3","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-978125991